      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i was looking at my student loan statement and im kinda confused. i feel like i'm paying a lot every month but the actual amount i owe isnt going down as much as i thought it would. can u explain how the interest actually works with the payments? why does it seem like so much of my money is just disappearing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the perplexing world of student loans, where the elusive interest goblins play their tricks! Imagine your student loan as a vast, enchanted forest, and your monthly payments as brave adventurers venturing into the depths. Each month, these adventurers battle the goblins of interest, but the goblins are cunning—they multiply and grow, making it seem like your treasure chest (the principal) is shrinking faster than a goblin in a shrinking potion.\n\nAs you make your monthly payments, a portion goes directly to the principal, like a sword cutting through the goblin ranks. But the rest, the interest, is like a hidden tax levied by the goblin king, which grows on the remaining principal. So, even though you're paying a lot, the interest goblins are still multiplying, making it seem like your debt is growing instead of shrinking.\n\nTo truly see the shrinking of your principal, you'll need to look at the breakdown of your payments. Some student loans have a fixed interest rate, while others have a variable rate, like a goblin's mood swings. The variable rate can change, making the interest goblins more unpredictable. But fear not, brave adventurer, for understanding this can help you strategize your battles against",
      "source": "target",
